dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-20260527T132416Z.log:166:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012XwetdufcwdpWGyy16uTVP","type":"tool_result","content":"85\tpursued in 0.7.0.\n86\t\n87\t**HITL responses (locked 2026-05-27):**\n88\t\n89\t1. **Recall floor**: ≥ 90 % recall@10 vs f32 ground truth on the\n90\t   AC-013 fixture (initial floor; tighten in later release).\n91\t2. **Embedder**: KEEP existing. Tier-1 #3 (smaller embeddings)\n92\t   and #5 (matryoshka) out of scope for 0.7.0.\n93\t3. **Metadata + partition_key schema**: YES, ship in 0.7.0 —\n94\t   bundled into Pack 1 of the implementation.\n95\t\n96\t**Implementation: 2 packs within 0.7.0.**\n97\t\n98\t- **Pack 1** — schema migration + ingest double-write. Adds\n99\t  `bit[768]` sibling column + metadata columns + partition_key\n100\t  to the vec0 schema; writer double-writes f32 + bit. No reader\n101\t  change yet; AC-013 stays pinned at the unindexed 2048/2327\n102\t  numbers. Correctness gate: migration round-trip test.\n103\t- **Pack 2** — query-path swap. `read_search_in_tx` becomes\n104\t  two-phase (bit KNN top-K → f32 rerank). Re-pins AC-013 to\n105\t  ≤ 80 / 300 ms and adds the recall-floor RED test\n106\t  (≥ 0.90 @ k=10).\n107\t\n108\tArchitectural-lever disposition: the binary-quant + rerank\n109\tquery shape is a **data-encoding change**, not a second\n110\tarchitectural lever (PCACHE2 already occupies that slot in\n111\t0.7.0). Both packs ship in 0.7.0. Fallback if a future reviewer\n112\tdisagrees on the lever counting: Pack 1 stays in 0.7.0;\n113\tPack 2 slips to 0.7.1.\n114\t\n115\tImplementation handoff: `dev/plans/prompts/0.7.0-PERF-VECTOR-QUANT-HANDOFF.md`.\n116\tAC-013 / AC-019 budgets in the revised-budgets ADR remain\n117\tplaceholders until Pack 2's canonical-CI measurement returns.\n118\t\n119\t### Test corpus (locked 2026-05-27)\n120\t\n121\tResearch at `dev/notes/0.7.0-test-corpus-research.md`. HITL\n122\tresponses:\n123\t\n124\t1. **Enron commit: OK** with the CMU April-2026 impersonation\n125\t   note on the corpus card.\n126\t2. **Synthetic cross-doc chain generator: in 0.7.0 scope** —\n127\t   needed to test the vector implementation; bundles with\n128\t   Pack 2.\n129\t3. **Recall floor 0.90 @ k=10**: current bar; revisit after\n130\t   empirical run.\n131\t4. **CI artifact**: cache the corpus in GitHub Actions cache.\n132\t   License-clean sources (CNN/DailyMail Apache-2.0, OpenAlex\n133\t   CC0, Enron) can additionally be committed; CC-BY-NC-SA\n134\t   sources (ELITR) live in cache only, fetched at cache miss.\n135\t5. **Partition_key: `source_type`** — locked. Supersedes the\n136\t   `kind` default in the Pack 1 handoff. Pack 1 schema MUST\n137\t   use `source_type` as the vec0 partition_key.\n138\t\n139\tDefault corpus version for Pack 2 RED tests: **Version B\n140\t(~10K docs)** per the research recommendation. Sources:\n141\tEnron / EnronQA (emails), QMSum + ELITR (meetings), PMC OA +\n142\tS2ORC + OpenAlex (academic), CNN/DailyMail (news), Imperative\n143\tTo-Do (todos), public daily-log repos + synthetic generator\n144\t(notes).\n145\t\n146\tCorpus-build handoff:\n147\t`dev/plans/prompts/0.7.0-CORPUS-BUILD-HANDOFF.md`.\n148\t\n149\tThe PCACHE2 stack is still the right lock for AC-012 / AC-020;\n150\tthe ANN-index addition is **orthogonal** (different bottleneck,\n151\tdifferent code path). Lock-flip on the revised-budgets ADR for\n152\tAC-012 / AC-020 should NOT block on the ANN-index slice; AC-013\n153\tand AC-019 budget rows in that ADR are placeholders pending the\n154\tANN slice's measurement.\n155\t\n156\t**AC-071 (top-K LIMIT default): additive opt-in (default unlimited)** ✅ LOCKED\n157\t\n158\t### Q2 — AC-020 architectural lever\n159\t\n160\t**PCACHE2 (Option 1)** ✅ LOCKED\n161\t\n162\t#### Clarification on \"how PCACHE2 combines with other tested settings\"\n163\t\n164\tThe locked production stack is **W4.1-stacked-O1**, which is one\n165\tbundle of co-enabled knobs:\n166\t\n167\t| Knob | What it is | How it composes with PCACHE2 |\n168\t|---|---|---|\n169\t| `SQLITE_CONFIG_PCACHE2` | Custom page-cache implementation (`pcache2.rs`, ~360 LOC). Replaces SQLite's default `pcache1`. | **The lever.** Process-start FFI. |\n170\t| `SQLITE_CONFIG_MEMSTATUS=0` | Disables SQLite's allocator-statistics mutex. | **Stacks additively.** Independent contention surface from the pcache1 mutex; both gains compound. |\n171\t| `page_size=8192` (writer pragma) | Increases SQLite B-tree page size from default 4K to 8K. | **Stacks additively.** Halves the number of pcache fetches per query; multiplies PCACHE2's per-fetch savings. |\n172\t| Reader pragmas: `cache_size=-262144`, `mmap_size=268435456`, `temp_store=MEMORY`, `synchronous=NORMAL` | Standard SQLite tuning: 256 MB cache cap, 256 MB mmap, in-memory temp tables, single-writer durability. | **Stacks additively.** Increases pcache hit rate (so PCACHE2's fast path runs more often) and reduces I/O sync overhead. |\n173\t| `SQLITE_CONFIG_PAGECACHE 1GB pre-alloc` | Pre-allocates 1 GB of pcache1 backing memory at process start. | **MUTUALLY EXCLUSIVE with PCACHE2.** PCACHE2 replaces the entire pcache subsystem; PAGECACHE has no effect when PCACHE2 is installed. The prototype omits PAGECACHE under PCACHE2; the production graduation should make this explicit (refuse to install both, or document that PAGECACHE is silently ignored). |\n174\t| `HashSet<key>` (unpinned eviction candidates inside PCACHE2) | Internal data structure for O(1) eviction lookup. | **Implementation detail of PCACHE2, not a separate lever.** The prototype uses a `HashSet` (best-effort eviction); production graduation should consider a doubly-linked-list LRU for better eviction quality under cache pressure. The AC-020 / AC-012 gates do not exercise tight cache pressure so the prototype suffices for the contract. |\n175\t| `LIMIT k=1000` (AC-012 query shape, Q4 lever) | Caps result-set size on the search verb. | **Independent of PCACHE2.** Helps AC-012 by reducing rows materialised; orthogonal to allocator/pcache contention. Recommended as opt-in per Q4 / AC-071 above. |\n176\t\n177\t**HITL also decided 2026-05-26: stay with W4.1-stacked-O1 as the\n178\tlocked 0.7.0 stack; do NOT pursue proper-LRU or `page_size=16384`\n179\t(alone or combined) in 0.7.0.** Rationale captured in\n180\t`dev/notes/pcache2-followups.md`: locked stack lands GREEN with\n181\tmaterial headroom; the measured 16K-solo prior (W4.0g) regressed\n182\ton AC-020; the LRU benefit is invisible on the AC fixtures and\n183\tneeds production-workload telemetry to size honestly. Both\n184\tvariations are eligible for a `0.8.0-PERF-PCACHE2-PRODUCTION`\n185\tslice keyed on the trigger conditions in the followups note.\n186\t\n187\t**Action items for the PCACHE2 production-graduation slice\n188\t(`0.7.0-PERF-PCACHE2`):**\n189\t\n190\t1. Replace `FATHOMDB_PERF_SQLITE_PCACHE2=1` env gate with a\n191\t   runtime-config field on `EngineRuntime::open` (whitepaper §13\n192\t   lookaside-config pattern).\n193\t2. Co-enable the full W4.1-stacked-O1 stack in `init_perf_*` /\n194\t   the corresponding production paths: MEMSTATUS_OFF + page_size=8192\n195\t   writer pragma + the four reader pragmas. These should be the\n196\t   default, not opt-in, under the locked release.\n197\t3. Ensure `SQLITE_CONFIG_PAGECACHE` is not also installed (it has\n198\t   no effect under PCACHE2 but the unused env var should be\n199\t   removed from the production path to avoid confusion).\n200\t4. Consider replacing PCACHE2's internal `HashSet` eviction with\n201\t   a proper LRU. Not required for the AC gates; required only\n202\t   under tight cache-pressure workloads. Land as a follow-up,\n203\t   noted in `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §13.\n204\t5. Pin the AC-020 RED-test bounds to the absolute-ms envelopes\n205\t   above (per Q1 AC-020 lock).\n206\t6. Pin the AC-012 RED-test budgets to 60/150 (per Q1 AC-012 lock).\n207\t\n208\t#### Other levers tested but not part of the locked stack\n209\t\n210\t| Lever ID | What it is | Result | Status |\n211\t|---|---|---|---|\n212\t| L-A0 baseline | No experiment env vars | Floor (W1.1) | Reference only |\n213\t| L-B4 reader synchronous=NORMAL | Component of reader pragmas | Stacked into W4.1-stacked-O1 | Locked |\n214\t| L-B5 reader cache+mmap+temp pragmas | Component of reader pragmas | Stacked into W4.1-stacked-O1 | Locked |\n215\t| L-Y1 MEMSTATUS=0 | Disable allocator stats | Stacked into W4.1-stacked-O1 | Locked |\n216\t| L-Y2 page_size=8192 | Writer page size | Stacked into W4.1-stacked-O1 | Locked |\n217\t| L-Y3 SQLITE_CONFIG_PAGECACHE pre-alloc | Pre-allocated pcache1 backing | Superseded by PCACHE2 | Not in locked stack |\n218\t| **L-D1 PCACHE2** | Custom xCreate/xFetch/xUnpin | Closes both gates | **Locked** |\n219\t| L-C1 LIMIT k=1000 | Search-shape lever | Independent; AC-071 additive | Opt-in (Q4) |\n220\t| L-D2 WAL2 | WAL2 patchset | **OUT OF SCOPE** per HITL | Rejected |\n221\t| L-D3 R-W split | Reader/writer pool separation | **OUT OF SCOPE** per HITL | Rejected |\n222\t| L-D4 libSQL / sqlite3mc swap | Vendor-SQLite swap | **OUT OF SCOPE** per HITL | Rejected |\n223\t\n224\t`ADR-0.7.0-ac020-architectural-lever.md` records WAL2 / R-W split\n225\t/ libSQL as rejected alternatives at lock-flip time.\n226\t\n227\t### Q4 — Top-K LIMIT shape\n228\t\n229\t**Additive opt-in (default unlimited; opt-in `--top-k` cap)** ✅ LOCKED\n230\t\n231\tPer the W4.1-stacked-O1 measurement, AC-012 closes on canonical\n232\tCI without any LIMIT changes (the `SEARCH_LIMIT=1000` env was\n233\tset during the dispatch but AC-012's measurement protocol uses\n234\tthe default-shape behavior — no cap applied). The LIMIT cap is a\n235\tknob for callers that want bounded latency, not a 0.7.0\n236\tbudget-closure dependency.\n237\t\n238\t## ADR lock-flip plan\n239\t\n240\tOnce the AC-013/AC-019 canonical-CI run completes:\n241\t\n242\t1. Update `dev/adr/ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised.md`:\n243\t   - `status: draft` → `status: locked`\n244\t   - AC-012 budget: `p50 ≤ 50 ms; p99 ≤ 200 ms` → `p50 ≤ 60 ms; p99 ≤ 150 ms`"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8d9c2010-470a-469e-a899-a4db3c31910c","uuid":"b4f00764-e259-4b7a-9ca0-84c076c53038","timestamp":"2026-05-27T13:24:57.116Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-20260527T132416Z/dev/plans/0.7.0-HITL-recommendations.md","content":"pursued in 0.7.0.\n\n**HITL responses (locked 2026-05-27):**\n\n1. **Recall floor**: ≥ 90 % recall@10 vs f32 ground truth on the\n   AC-013 fixture (initial floor; tighten in later release).\n2. **Embedder**: KEEP existing. Tier-1 #3 (smaller embeddings)\n   and #5 (matryoshka) out of scope for 0.7.0.\n3. **Metadata + partition_key schema**: YES, ship in 0.7.0 —\n   bundled into Pack 1 of the implementation.\n\n**Implementation: 2 packs within 0.7.0.**\n\n- **Pack 1** — schema migration + ingest double-write. Adds\n  `bit[768]` sibling column + metadata columns + partition_key\n  to the vec0 schema; writer double-writes f32 + bit. No reader\n  change yet; AC-013 stays pinned at the unindexed 2048/2327\n  numbers. Correctness gate: migration round-trip test.\n- **Pack 2** — query-path swap. `read_search_in_tx` becomes\n  two-phase (bit KNN top-K → f32 rerank). Re-pins AC-013 to\n  ≤ 80 / 300 ms and adds the recall-floor RED test\n  (≥ 0.90 @ k=10).\n\nArchitectural-lever disposition: the binary-quant + rerank\nquery shape is a **data-encoding change**, not a second\narchitectural lever (PCACHE2 already occupies that slot in\n0.7.0). Both packs ship in 0.7.0. Fallback if a future reviewer\ndisagrees on the lever counting: Pack 1 stays in 0.7.0;\nPack 2 slips to 0.7.1.\n\nImplementation handoff: `dev/plans/prompts/0.7.0-PERF-VECTOR-QUANT-HANDOFF.md`.\nAC-013 / AC-019 budgets in the revised-budgets ADR remain\nplaceholders until Pack 2's canonical-CI measurement returns.\n\n### Test corpus (locked 2026-05-27)\n\nResearch at `dev/notes/0.7.0-test-corpus-research.md`. HITL\nresponses:\n\n1. **Enron commit: OK** with the CMU April-2026 impersonation\n   note on the corpus card.\n2. **Synthetic cross-doc chain generator: in 0.7.0 scope** —\n   needed to test the vector implementation; bundles with\n   Pack 2.\n3. **Recall floor 0.90 @ k=10**: current bar; revisit after\n   empirical run.\n4. **CI artifact**: cache the corpus in GitHub Actions cache.\n   License-clean sources (CNN/DailyMail Apache-2.0, OpenAlex\n   CC0, Enron) can additionally be committed; CC-BY-NC-SA\n   sources (ELITR) live in cache only, fetched at cache miss.\n5. **Partition_key: `source_type`** — locked. Supersedes the\n   `kind` default in the Pack 1 handoff. Pack 1 schema MUST\n   use `source_type` as the vec0 partition_key.\n\nDefault corpus version for Pack 2 RED tests: **Version B\n(~10K docs)** per the research recommendation. Sources:\nEnron / EnronQA (emails), QMSum + ELITR (meetings), PMC OA +\nS2ORC + OpenAlex (academic), CNN/DailyMail (news), Imperative\nTo-Do (todos), public daily-log repos + synthetic generator\n(notes).\n\nCorpus-build handoff:\n`dev/plans/prompts/0.7.0-CORPUS-BUILD-HANDOFF.md`.\n\nThe PCACHE2 stack is still the right lock for AC-012 / AC-020;\nthe ANN-index addition is **orthogonal** (different bottleneck,\ndifferent code path). Lock-flip on the revised-budgets ADR for\nAC-012 / AC-020 should NOT block on the ANN-index slice; AC-013\nand AC-019 budget rows in that ADR are placeholders pending the\nANN slice's measurement.\n\n**AC-071 (top-K LIMIT default): additive opt-in (default unlimited)** ✅ LOCKED\n\n### Q2 — AC-020 architectural lever\n\n**PCACHE2 (Option 1)** ✅ LOCKED\n\n#### Clarification on \"how PCACHE2 combines with other tested settings\"\n\nThe locked production stack is **W4.1-stacked-O1**, which is one\nbundle of co-enabled knobs:\n\n| Knob | What it is | How it composes with PCACHE2 |\n|---|---|---|\n| `SQLITE_CONFIG_PCACHE2` | Custom page-cache implementation (`pcache2.rs`, ~360 LOC). Replaces SQLite's default `pcache1`. | **The lever.** Process-start FFI. |\n| `SQLITE_CONFIG_MEMSTATUS=0` | Disables SQLite's allocator-statistics mutex. | **Stacks additively.** Independent contention surface from the pcache1 mutex; both gains compound. |\n| `page_size=8192` (writer pragma) | Increases SQLite B-tree page size from default 4K to 8K. | **Stacks additively.** Halves the number of pcache fetches per query; multiplies PCACHE2's per-fetch savings. |\n| Reader pragmas: `cache_size=-262144`, `mmap_size=268435456`, `temp_store=MEMORY`, `synchronous=NORMAL` | Standard SQLite tuning: 256 MB cache cap, 256 MB mmap, in-memory temp tables, single-writer durability. | **Stacks additively.** Increases pcache hit rate (so PCACHE2's fast path runs more often) and reduces I/O sync overhead. |\n| `SQLITE_CONFIG_PAGECACHE 1GB pre-alloc` | Pre-allocates 1 GB of pcache1 backing memory at process start. | **MUTUALLY EXCLUSIVE with PCACHE2.** PCACHE2 replaces the entire pcache subsystem; PAGECACHE has no effect when PCACHE2 is installed. The prototype omits PAGECACHE under PCACHE2; the production graduation should make this explicit (refuse to install both, or document that PAGECACHE is silently ignored). |\n| `HashSet<key>` (unpinned eviction candidates inside PCACHE2) | Internal data structure for O(1) eviction lookup. | **Implementation detail of PCACHE2, not a separate lever.** The prototype uses a `HashSet` (best-effort eviction); production graduation should consider a doubly-linked-list LRU for better eviction quality under cache pressure. The AC-020 / AC-012 gates do not exercise tight cache pressure so the prototype suffices for the contract. |\n| `LIMIT k=1000` (AC-012 query shape, Q4 lever) | Caps result-set size on the search verb. | **Independent of PCACHE2.** Helps AC-012 by reducing rows materialised; orthogonal to allocator/pcache contention. Recommended as opt-in per Q4 / AC-071 above. |\n\n**HITL also decided 2026-05-26: stay with W4.1-stacked-O1 as the\nlocked 0.7.0 stack; do NOT pursue proper-LRU or `page_size=16384`\n(alone or combined) in 0.7.0.** Rationale captured in\n`dev/notes/pcache2-followups.md`: locked stack lands GREEN with\nmaterial headroom; the measured 16K-solo prior (W4.0g) regressed\non AC-020; the LRU benefit is invisible on the AC fixtures and\nneeds production-workload telemetry to size honestly. Both\nvariations are eligible for a `0.8.0-PERF-PCACHE2-PRODUCTION`\nslice keyed on the trigger conditions in the followups note.\n\n**Action items for the PCACHE2 production-graduation slice\n(`0.7.0-PERF-PCACHE2`):**\n\n1. Replace `FATHOMDB_PERF_SQLITE_PCACHE2=1` env gate with a\n   runtime-config field on `EngineRuntime::open` (whitepaper §13\n   lookaside-config pattern).\n2. Co-enable the full W4.1-stacked-O1 stack in `init_perf_*` /\n   the corresponding production paths: MEMSTATUS_OFF + page_size=8192\n   writer pragma + the four reader pragmas. These should be the\n   default, not opt-in, under the locked release.\n3. Ensure `SQLITE_CONFIG_PAGECACHE` is not also installed (it has\n   no effect under PCACHE2 but the unused env var should be\n   removed from the production path to avoid confusion).\n4. Consider replacing PCACHE2's internal `HashSet` eviction with\n   a proper LRU. Not required for the AC gates; required only\n   under tight cache-pressure workloads. Land as a follow-up,\n   noted in `dev/notes/performance-whitepaper-notes.md` §13.\n5. Pin the AC-020 RED-test bounds to the absolute-ms envelopes\n   above (per Q1 AC-020 lock).\n6. Pin the AC-012 RED-test budgets to 60/150 (per Q1 AC-012 lock).\n\n#### Other levers tested but not part of the locked stack\n\n| Lever ID | What it is | Result | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| L-A0 baseline | No experiment env vars | Floor (W1.1) | Reference only |\n| L-B4 reader synchronous=NORMAL | Component of reader pragmas | Stacked into W4.1-stacked-O1 | Locked |\n| L-B5 reader cache+mmap+temp pragmas | Component of reader pragmas | Stacked into W4.1-stacked-O1 | Locked |\n| L-Y1 MEMSTATUS=0 | Disable allocator stats | Stacked into W4.1-stacked-O1 | Locked |\n| L-Y2 page_size=8192 | Writer page size | Stacked into W4.1-stacked-O1 | Locked |\n| L-Y3 SQLITE_CONFIG_PAGECACHE pre-alloc | Pre-allocated pcache1 backing | Superseded by PCACHE2 | Not in locked stack |\n| **L-D1 PCACHE2** | Custom xCreate/xFetch/xUnpin | Closes both gates | **Locked** |\n| L-C1 LIMIT k=1000 | Search-shape lever | Independent; AC-071 additive | Opt-in (Q4) |\n| L-D2 WAL2 | WAL2 patchset | **OUT OF SCOPE** per HITL | Rejected |\n| L-D3 R-W split | Reader/writer pool separation | **OUT OF SCOPE** per HITL | Rejected |\n| L-D4 libSQL / sqlite3mc swap | Vendor-SQLite swap | **OUT OF SCOPE** per HITL | Rejected |\n\n`ADR-0.7.0-ac020-architectural-lever.md` records WAL2 / R-W split\n/ libSQL as rejected alternatives at lock-flip time.\n\n### Q4 — Top-K LIMIT shape\n\n**Additive opt-in (default unlimited; opt-in `--top-k` cap)** ✅ LOCKED\n\nPer the W4.1-stacked-O1 measurement, AC-012 closes on canonical\nCI without any LIMIT changes (the `SEARCH_LIMIT=1000` env was\nset during the dispatch but AC-012's measurement protocol uses\nthe default-shape behavior — no cap applied). The LIMIT cap is a\nknob for callers that want bounded latency, not a 0.7.0\nbudget-closure dependency.\n\n## ADR lock-flip plan\n\nOnce the AC-013/AC-019 canonical-CI run completes:\n\n1. Update `dev/adr/ADR-0.7.0-text-query-latency-gates-revised.md`:\n   - `status: draft` → `status: locked`\n   - AC-012 budget: `p50 ≤ 50 ms; p99 ≤ 200 ms` → `p50 ≤ 60 ms; p99 ≤ 150 ms`","numLines":160,"startLine":85,"totalLines":296}}}
dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-20260527T132416Z.log:169:{"type":"stream_event","event":{"type":"content_block_start","index":0,"content_block":{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01EfFiHisgsQkNXPNoocLv9a","name":"Bash","input":{},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}},"session_id":"8d9c2010-470a-469e-a899-a4db3c31910c","parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"9d0bfbc5-ca69-4772-8942-ef97beae12b2"}
dev/plans/runs/0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-20260527T132416Z.log:198:{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QXqFEvFTvB82dMr2Ds3XE9","type":"tool_result","content":"60\ttechnique that **shrinks the bytes-per-row** or **shrinks the row\n61\tcount** translates ~linearly to latency.\n62\t\n63\t### 1. Metadata prefiltering\n64\t\n65\t- **Mechanism.** `vec0` (sqlite-vec ≥ 0.1.6) supports auxiliary\n66\t  metadata columns and partition-key columns; KNN can be pre-filtered\n67\t  with `WHERE kind = ?` so distance compute runs only over the\n68\t  matching chunk(s). Cited:\n69\t  [alexgarcia.xyz blog — metadata release](https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html);\n70\t  vec0 features page lists up to 16 metadata columns and 4 partition\n71\t  keys.\n72\t- **Expected gain.** Scales with selectivity. If FathomDB carries 8\n73\t  vector kinds with rough uniformity, prefiltering by `kind` cuts\n74\t  scanned rows ~8× ⇒ ~256 ms. AC-013's fixture seeds a *single*\n75\t  `\"doc\"` kind (`tests/perf_gates.rs:350`), so the benchmark itself\n76\t  gets **no benefit** from `kind` prefiltering. Real workloads do.\n77\t- **Implementation cost.** Schema migration (add metadata + partition\n78\t  cols to `vector_default` or split into per-kind tables);\n79\t  `engine.search()` API extension to accept filter predicates;\n80\t  ingest path change in `_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert\n81\t  (`lib.rs:2846`). Moderate.\n82\t- **Recall / correctness.** Exact within the filter set — semantics\n83\t  change (results restricted), not approximated.\n84\t- **Compatibility.** Plays cleanly with writer lock + projection\n85\t  cursor; vec0 partition keys are chunk-organised so writes scale\n86\t  per partition.\n87\t\n88\t**Verdict on its own: insufficient for AC-013's synthetic\n89\tsingle-kind fixture; valuable for real workloads but not load-bearing\n90\tfor the gate.**\n91\t\n92\t### 2. Partition keys (physical / logical)\n93\t\n94\t- **Mechanism.** Partition-key columns on `vec0` (sqlite-vec\n95\t  feature; max 4) physically chunk storage. Logical alternative:\n96\t  N per-kind `vec0` tables.\n97\t- **Gain.** Same scaling as metadata prefilter; for AC-013's\n98\t  single-kind fixture, zero. For domain workloads with k=8 partitions\n99\t  → ~8× cheaper scans (~250 ms).\n100\t- **Cost.** Either a multi-table search planner (logical) or schema\n101\t  migration (partition_key). Logical option additionally creates a\n102\t  fan-out merge problem at the search layer.\n103\t- **Recall.** Exact within partition set.\n104\t- **Compatibility.** Per-table flavour is incompatible with the\n105\t  current single `vector_default` table assumption baked into\n106\t  `read_search_in_tx`; partition_key flavour is a simpler change.\n107\t\n108\t**Verdict: same as #1 — orthogonal to the gate, but worth shipping\n109\ttogether if we do a vec0 migration anyway.**\n110\t\n111\t### 3. Smaller embeddings (lower dim)\n112\t\n113\t- **Mechanism.** dim 768 → 384 (MiniLM-L6) halves distance compute;\n114\t  → 256 cuts 3×; → 128 cuts 6×.\n115\t- **Gain (alone).** 384 ⇒ ~1024 ms; 128 ⇒ ~340 ms. Neither closes\n116\t  the 25–40× gap by itself.\n117\t- **Cost.** This is **the embedder identity**, not a vec0 setting.\n118\t  `EmbedderIdentity` is profile-pinned via\n119\t  `_fathomdb_embedder_profiles` (`lib.rs:3248-3260`); switching\n120\t  embedders requires a corpus rebuild and a profile rotation. Not a\n121\t  knob we can flip without writer cooperation and a re-embedding\n122\t  pass.\n123\t- **Recall.** Domain-dependent; MTEB shows ~3–6 pp recall drop from\n124\t  768→384 for general-purpose embedders.\n125\t- **Compatibility.** Touches the embedder contract and the schema\n126\t  pinning logic. **HITL Q1: do we have the appetite to switch the\n127\t  reference embedder in 0.7.0?** Default assumption: no.\n128\t\n129\t**Verdict: out of scope for 0.7.0 unless HITL signals otherwise.**\n130\t\n131\t### 4. Binary / int8 quantization (THE LEVER)\n132\t\n133\t- **Mechanism.** Replace the f32 column with `bit[768]` or\n134\t  `int8[768]`. sqlite-vec supports both natively in `vec0`\n135\t  (`bit[N]`, `int8[N]` declarations; cited:\n136\t  [sqlite-vec API reference / DeepWiki](https://deepwiki.com/asg017/sqlite-vec/3-api-reference);\n137\t  [binary quantization guide](https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html)).\n138\t  Binary distance becomes Hamming (popcount xor) on 96 bytes/row\n139\t  vs 3072 bytes/row of f32 — **32× narrower**, plus 4× lighter\n140\t  arithmetic. Int8 is 4× narrower with SIMD-able dot products.\n141\t- **Gain.** Binary: 32× storage × ~1× arithmetic-density advantage\n142\t  ⇒ 30–50× in practice on memory-bound scans. Published benches\n143\t  (Kyle Howells, Cohere) show 15–40× faster than f32 brute force at\n144\t  ~85–95 % recall@10 with **rerank-on-f32**. Expected p50 if we\n145\t  binarize: **~50–100 ms** for 1 M rows. Int8 alone: 4–8× ⇒\n146\t  ~250–500 ms (borderline on the p99 = 300 ms budget).\n147\t- **Cost.** Schema migration (add `embedding_bin bit[768]` column\n148\t  or a sibling `vector_default_bin` table); ingest path adds a\n149\t  `vec_quantize_binary()` call alongside the f32 insert; query path\n150\t  becomes a two-phase: **bit-distance prefilter → f32 rerank** of\n151\t  the top ~256 candidates. The f32 column is retained for rerank\n152\t  (so storage grows 1.03×, not shrinks). All changes are SQL-level\n153\t  and application-side; no SQLite build flags. sqlite-vec ≥ 0.1.7\n154\t  (our pinned version) already ships the relevant types per\n155\t  [release notes](https://github.com/asg017/sqlite-vec/releases) —\n156\t  no upgrade required to land bit/int8, though upgrading to 0.1.9\n157\t  is low-risk and unlocks the constraint-column KNN refinements.\n158\t- **Recall.** Binary alone: ~70–80 % @ k=10. Binary + f32 rerank\n159\t  on top-K (K = 4–8 × k): ~95–99 % @ k=10, equivalent to brute\n160\t  force for most practical purposes. **HITL Q2: what's the recall\n161\t  floor we'll enforce in the AC-013 RED test?** Suggested: ≥ 90 %\n162\t  recall@10 vs f32 ground truth on the AC-013 fixture.\n163\t- **Compatibility.** Single-writer lock and projection cursor are\n164\t  not affected — both columns commit in the same writer\n165\t  transaction. `VaryingEmbedder` produces normalised f32; binary\n166\t  quantization preserves the sign-mass pattern it encodes, so the\n167\t  fixture remains discriminative.\n168\t\n169\t**Verdict: binary + f32 rerank is the single highest-leverage Tier-1\n170\ttechnique. Plausibly closes the gate alone.**\n171\t\n172\t### 5. Matryoshka / truncated dimensions\n173\t\n174\t- **Mechanism.** Run KNN against a 128-d prefix, rerank on full 768.\n175\t- **Gain.** ~6× on the prefilter pass ⇒ ~340 ms. Less leverage than\n176\t  binary; binary already wins on bandwidth.\n177\t- **Cost.** Requires a Matryoshka-trained embedder (`nomic-embed\n178\t  v1.5`, `text-embedding-3-*`). VaryingEmbedder is not Matryoshka;\n179\t  the AC-013 fixture wouldn't exhibit the recall property."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8d9c2010-470a-469e-a899-a4db3c31910c","uuid":"8f7c77f8-4a10-4ecd-a1b0-6780c6b6ac48","timestamp":"2026-05-27T13:25:05.335Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/fdb-0.7.0-PVQ-P1-DESIGN-20260527T132416Z/dev/notes/0.7.0-vector-cost-research.md","content":"technique that **shrinks the bytes-per-row** or **shrinks the row\ncount** translates ~linearly to latency.\n\n### 1. Metadata prefiltering\n\n- **Mechanism.** `vec0` (sqlite-vec ≥ 0.1.6) supports auxiliary\n  metadata columns and partition-key columns; KNN can be pre-filtered\n  with `WHERE kind = ?` so distance compute runs only over the\n  matching chunk(s). Cited:\n  [alexgarcia.xyz blog — metadata release](https://alexgarcia.xyz/blog/2024/sqlite-vec-metadata-release/index.html);\n  vec0 features page lists up to 16 metadata columns and 4 partition\n  keys.\n- **Expected gain.** Scales with selectivity. If FathomDB carries 8\n  vector kinds with rough uniformity, prefiltering by `kind` cuts\n  scanned rows ~8× ⇒ ~256 ms. AC-013's fixture seeds a *single*\n  `\"doc\"` kind (`tests/perf_gates.rs:350`), so the benchmark itself\n  gets **no benefit** from `kind` prefiltering. Real workloads do.\n- **Implementation cost.** Schema migration (add metadata + partition\n  cols to `vector_default` or split into per-kind tables);\n  `engine.search()` API extension to accept filter predicates;\n  ingest path change in `_fathomdb_vector_rows` insert\n  (`lib.rs:2846`). Moderate.\n- **Recall / correctness.** Exact within the filter set — semantics\n  change (results restricted), not approximated.\n- **Compatibility.** Plays cleanly with writer lock + projection\n  cursor; vec0 partition keys are chunk-organised so writes scale\n  per partition.\n\n**Verdict on its own: insufficient for AC-013's synthetic\nsingle-kind fixture; valuable for real workloads but not load-bearing\nfor the gate.**\n\n### 2. Partition keys (physical / logical)\n\n- **Mechanism.** Partition-key columns on `vec0` (sqlite-vec\n  feature; max 4) physically chunk storage. Logical alternative:\n  N per-kind `vec0` tables.\n- **Gain.** Same scaling as metadata prefilter; for AC-013's\n  single-kind fixture, zero. For domain workloads with k=8 partitions\n  → ~8× cheaper scans (~250 ms).\n- **Cost.** Either a multi-table search planner (logical) or schema\n  migration (partition_key). Logical option additionally creates a\n  fan-out merge problem at the search layer.\n- **Recall.** Exact within partition set.\n- **Compatibility.** Per-table flavour is incompatible with the\n  current single `vector_default` table assumption baked into\n  `read_search_in_tx`; partition_key flavour is a simpler change.\n\n**Verdict: same as #1 — orthogonal to the gate, but worth shipping\ntogether if we do a vec0 migration anyway.**\n\n### 3. Smaller embeddings (lower dim)\n\n- **Mechanism.** dim 768 → 384 (MiniLM-L6) halves distance compute;\n  → 256 cuts 3×; → 128 cuts 6×.\n- **Gain (alone).** 384 ⇒ ~1024 ms; 128 ⇒ ~340 ms. Neither closes\n  the 25–40× gap by itself.\n- **Cost.** This is **the embedder identity**, not a vec0 setting.\n  `EmbedderIdentity` is profile-pinned via\n  `_fathomdb_embedder_profiles` (`lib.rs:3248-3260`); switching\n  embedders requires a corpus rebuild and a profile rotation. Not a\n  knob we can flip without writer cooperation and a re-embedding\n  pass.\n- **Recall.** Domain-dependent; MTEB shows ~3–6 pp recall drop from\n  768→384 for general-purpose embedders.\n- **Compatibility.** Touches the embedder contract and the schema\n  pinning logic. **HITL Q1: do we have the appetite to switch the\n  reference embedder in 0.7.0?** Default assumption: no.\n\n**Verdict: out of scope for 0.7.0 unless HITL signals otherwise.**\n\n### 4. Binary / int8 quantization (THE LEVER)\n\n- **Mechanism.** Replace the f32 column with `bit[768]` or\n  `int8[768]`. sqlite-vec supports both natively in `vec0`\n  (`bit[N]`, `int8[N]` declarations; cited:\n  [sqlite-vec API reference / DeepWiki](https://deepwiki.com/asg017/sqlite-vec/3-api-reference);\n  [binary quantization guide](https://alexgarcia.xyz/sqlite-vec/guides/binary-quant.html)).\n  Binary distance becomes Hamming (popcount xor) on 96 bytes/row\n  vs 3072 bytes/row of f32 — **32× narrower**, plus 4× lighter\n  arithmetic. Int8 is 4× narrower with SIMD-able dot products.\n- **Gain.** Binary: 32× storage × ~1× arithmetic-density advantage\n  ⇒ 30–50× in practice on memory-bound scans. Published benches\n  (Kyle Howells, Cohere) show 15–40× faster than f32 brute force at\n  ~85–95 % recall@10 with **rerank-on-f32**. Expected p50 if we\n  binarize: **~50–100 ms** for 1 M rows. Int8 alone: 4–8× ⇒\n  ~250–500 ms (borderline on the p99 = 300 ms budget).\n- **Cost.** Schema migration (add `embedding_bin bit[768]` column\n  or a sibling `vector_default_bin` table); ingest path adds a\n  `vec_quantize_binary()` call alongside the f32 insert; query path\n  becomes a two-phase: **bit-distance prefilter → f32 rerank** of\n  the top ~256 candidates. The f32 column is retained for rerank\n  (so storage grows 1.03×, not shrinks). All changes are SQL-level\n  and application-side; no SQLite build flags. sqlite-vec ≥ 0.1.7\n  (our pinned version) already ships the relevant types per\n  [release notes](https://github.com/asg017/sqlite-vec/releases) —\n  no upgrade required to land bit/int8, though upgrading to 0.1.9\n  is low-risk and unlocks the constraint-column KNN refinements.\n- **Recall.** Binary alone: ~70–80 % @ k=10. Binary + f32 rerank\n  on top-K (K = 4–8 × k): ~95–99 % @ k=10, equivalent to brute\n  force for most practical purposes. **HITL Q2: what's the recall\n  floor we'll enforce in the AC-013 RED test?** Suggested: ≥ 90 %\n  recall@10 vs f32 ground truth on the AC-013 fixture.\n- **Compatibility.** Single-writer lock and projection cursor are\n  not affected — both columns commit in the same writer\n  transaction. `VaryingEmbedder` produces normalised f32; binary\n  quantization preserves the sign-mass pattern it encodes, so the\n  fixture remains discriminative.\n\n**Verdict: binary + f32 rerank is the single highest-leverage Tier-1\ntechnique. Plausibly closes the gate alone.**\n\n### 5. Matryoshka / truncated dimensions\n\n- **Mechanism.** Run KNN against a 128-d prefix, rerank on full 768.\n- **Gain.** ~6× on the prefilter pass ⇒ ~340 ms. Less leverage than\n  binary; binary already wins on bandwidth.\n- **Cost.** Requires a Matryoshka-trained embedder (`nomic-embed\n  v1.5`, `text-embedding-3-*`). VaryingEmbedder is not Matryoshka;\n  the AC-013 fixture wouldn't exhibit the recall property.","numLines":120,"startLine":60,"totalLines":419}}}
